{"key":"post-12689990","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12689990</id>\n<content>Confirmation of what?&amp;nbsp; The amount of gypsum?&amp;nbsp; If you're using ten percent gypsum by weight, that's plenty.&amp;nbsp; I've been experimenting with using less gypsum on my shiitake blocks, and so far I haven't seen any reduction in performance until I get less than 5% by volume, which is around 2 1/2% by weight.&amp;nbsp; Bear in mind that's using hardwoods, which may be somewhat higher in minerals than what you're using for substrate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum supplies calcium and sulfur, both of which are essential for good fruitbody formation.&amp;nbsp; Using too much doesn't really hurt, it just doesn't help to use more than is needed by the mycelium.&amp;nbsp; However, if your substrate is lacking these minerals, failure to use enough gypsum will impact yields substantially.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12690028</next>\n<prev>12689146</prev>\n<first>12672191</first>\n<last>12690264</last>\n<when>1275739778</when>\n<utime>06/05/10 03:09 PM</utime>\n</post>"}